       (.home-hero__img, position:absolute) paints in the later
       "positioned descendants" layer on top of it — the opaque photo
       visually covers the accent panel's branded content completely,
       reproducing as "the hero disappears" (confirmed via
       elementFromPoint()/computed-style measurement at 375x667: the
       header sits at the expected z-index, but the accent panel's own
       content was unreachable/invisible under the image). Fix: keep the
       accent panel in normal flow (still full-width, still after the
       caption in source) but make it a positioned element via
       position:relative instead of static, so its existing z-index: 3
       (inherited from the desktop rule) takes effect again and it paints
       above the image/scrim, exactly like it already does on desktop. */
    .home-hero__accent {
      position: relative;
      /* Neutralize the desktop rule's right/bottom offsets — under
         position:relative (unlike static) they'd otherwise shift this
         box up-and-left by --space-md, since relative positioning still
